  "prompt": "What is a good website for free books?",
  "response": "There are many great websites for free books! Here are some of the best, categorized by what they offer:\n\n**For Classic Literature (Public Domain):**\n\n*   **Project Gutenberg (gutenberg.org):** This is the granddaddy of free ebook sites. It has a massive collection of over 70,000 ebooks, mostly classics whose copyright has expired.  You can read online, or download in various formats like EPUB, Kindle, and plain text.\n*   **Standard Ebooks (standardebooks.org):**  Focuses on providing high-quality, meticulously formatted versions of public domain ebooks.  Their books look great on any device.  Excellent typography and consistent formatting.\n*   **LibriVox (librivox.org):** Offers audiobooks of public domain works read by volunteers. Great for listening while you're commuting or doing chores.\n*   **Internet Archive (archive.org):** A vast digital library with scanned books, texts, audio, video, and more. You can often borrow books (digital lending library) or read them online.\n\n**For Modern & Contemporary Free Books (Legal & Promotional):**\n\n*   **Amazon Kindle Store (amazon.com):**  Search for \"free ebooks\" on the Kindle store. Amazon often has promotional free ebooks available, including books by independent authors. You don't need a Kindle device to read them, you can use the Kindle app on your phone or computer. *Be sure to check reviews and author before downloading!*\n*   **BookBub (bookbub.com):**  A daily email service that alerts you to limited-time deals on ebooks, including free ones.  They curate deals based on your preferences.\n*   **ManyBooks (manybooks.net):** Offers a wide range of free ebooks, including both classic literature and works by contemporary authors.\n*   **Freebooksy (freebooksy.com):** Similar to BookBub, Freebooksy focuses on alerting you to free ebooks, curated by genre.\n*   **Smashwords (smashwords.com):**  A platform for independent authors. Many authors offer their books for free as a way to gain exposure.\n*   **Project Gutenberg Canada (gutenberg.ca):** Similar to Project Gutenberg, but focuses on books in the public domain in Canada.  This might include titles that are still under copyright in the US.\n\n**For Online Reading Platforms:**\n\n*   **Wattpad (wattpad.com):**  A popular platform for aspiring writers to share their stories, often for free. Great for discovering new and emerging authors.  Lots of fan fiction.\n*   **Royal Road (royalroad.com):**  Similar to Wattpad, but focuses more on fantasy and science fiction.\n*   **Archive of Our Own (archiveofourown.org):** (AO3)  A large and popular fanfiction archive.\n\n**Important Considerations:**\n\n*   **Copyright:**  Always be mindful of copyright.  Downloading copyrighted books without permission is illegal.  Stick to the sources listed above that provide legal access to free books.\n*   **Format:**  Make sure the website offers books in a format that is compatible with your e-reader or device (e.g., EPUB, MOBI, PDF).\n*   **Quality:**  The quality of free ebooks can vary.  Look for well-formatted editions from reputable sources like Standard Ebooks or Project Gutenberg.  Read reviews before downloading contemporary works.\n*   **Beware of Scams:** Be cautious of websites that ask for excessive personal information or require you to download suspicious software.\n\nI recommend starting with Project Gutenberg or Standard Ebooks for classic literature and then exploring Amazon, BookBub, and Freebooksy for contemporary freebies.  Wattpad and Royal Road are good options if you're interested in discovering new and emerging authors and fan fiction.  Happy reading!\n",
